<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900925-0164</DOCNO><DOCID>900925-0164.</DOCID><HL>   Letters to the Editor:   Worm's-Eye View</HL><DATE>09/25/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A23</SO><LP>   Your Aug. 24 article &quot;Good News for Worms: Study FindsGenetic Clue to Aging in Nematode&quot; notes that the recentsuccessful mutating of a single gene in the roundworm,&quot;Caenorhabditis elegans,&quot; creates &quot;what might be called theMethuselahs of the annelid world.&quot; May I point out thatannelids, which are segmented worms (earthworms, etc.) belongto an entirely different phylum than the roundworms, whichare nematodes. The nematodes are a giant step below on theevolutionary ladder from the annelids.   John A. Stone</LP><TEXT>   Venice, Fla.</TEXT></DOC>